{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017HjN6fNcAbndBTdJt1Hy86","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 9 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Two failures, two distinct root causes that share a common theme: the threshold gate has absolute veto power over candidates that pass all structural/hard filters, with no fallback when the candidate pool is small or the positional signal is unambiguous.\n     6→\n     7→The fixes are:\n     8→\n     9→1. **Pre-threshold bilingual protection** — move first-line detection before threshold filtering so ALL_CAPS bonuses can't inflate the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    10→2. **Empty-pool fallback** — when threshold filtering discards every candidate, fall back to the best positional candidate from the hard-filter-passing pool.\n    11→\n    12→These are complementary: fix 1 prevents failure 2 (Faszerowana papryka) by keeping the correct candidate in `selected`; fix 2 prevents failure 1 (Baked Eggs) by ensuring a sole survivor is never silently discarded.\n    13→\n    14→---\n    15→\n    16→## Failure 1: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" → `''`\n    17→\n    18→### Root Cause\n    19→\n    20→The pre-merge step correctly produces the full candidate. It passes all hard filters (54 chars, no measurements, no metadata, not garbled). But the embedding scorer computes `rawScore = titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim)` and because ingredient words (Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce, Coriander) are semantically close to `HEADER_REFERENCE` (\"ingredients list, cooking directions\"), `headerSim ≈ titleSim` or `headerSim > titleSim`. The rawScore is near zero or negative. No bonus applies (mixed-case, not structural heading). The final score falls below `threshold = max(0.08, ...)` and the candidate is filtered out, returning `undefined`.\n    21→\n    22→The fundamental issue: **embeddings cannot distinguish \"dish named after its ingredients\" from \"fragment of an ingredient list\"**. The hard filters already make that distinction (ingredient lists have measurements, start with numbers, etc.), but their verdict is overruled by the embedding threshold.\n    23→\n    24→### Fix: Empty-pool fallback\n    25→\n    26→After the existing threshold filter (`let selected = scored.filter(s => s.score >= threshold)`), add a fallback:\n    27→\n    28→```typescript\n    29→// BEFORE (line ~389):\n    30→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    31→\n    32→// AFTER:\n    33→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    34→\n    35→// Empty-pool fallback: when threshold filtering discards every candidate,\n    36→// the hard filters' structural verdict should not be overruled by weak\n    37→// embedding differentiation. Return the best positional candidate.\n    38→if (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n    39→  // Prefer candidates near the top of the document (position 0 = most likely title).\n    40→  // Among ties, prefer higher score.\n    41→  const fallback = scored\n    42→    .slice()\n    43→    .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n    44→  selected = [fallback[0]];\n    45→}\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→**Why this is safe:** Every candidate in `scored` already passed `passesHardFilters()` — no measurements, no metadata, no garbled text, not starting with a number, not lowercase-initial. If the entire pool of structurally-valid candidates has weak embedding differentiation, position is the strongest remaining signal (recipe titles appear at the top of the page). This fallback only fires when `selected` would otherwise be empty, so it cannot degrade any currently-passing test.\n    49→\n    50→### Expected behavior after fix\n    51→\n    52→- \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" is the only candidate in `scored` (the body text, ingredients, and metadata all fail hard filters).\n    53→- Threshold filter discards it (score < 0.08).\n    54→- Fallback selects it as the sole candidate → returns the correct title.\n    55→\n    56→---\n    57→\n    58→## Failure 2: \"Faszerowana papryka\" → `'PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM'`\n    59→\n    60→### Root Cause\n    61→\n    62→The first-line protection (lines 468–479) was designed for exactly this case: mixed-case title at position 0 followed by ALL_CAPS subtitle. But the protection runs **after** threshold filtering. The ALL_CAPS candidate \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" receives `+0.08` allCapsBonus + `+0.10` structuralBonus = `+0.18` on top of its rawScore. This inflates the threshold via `bestThresholdScore * 0.7`. The Polish mixed-case title \"Faszerowana papryka\" has a low rawScore (MiniLM is English-centric; short Polish text has low cosine similarity to the English TITLE_REFERENCE) and no bonuses. It falls below the inflated threshold, never enters `selected`, and the protection — which checks `selected.find(s => s.position === 0)` — silently becomes a no-op.\n    63→\n    64→The design is self-defeating: the protection requires the correct title to have already survived the threshold independently, but it's needed precisely when the title **cannot** survive the threshold.\n    65→\n    66→### Fix: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n    67→\n    68→Move the bilingual detection to operate on the full `scored` array (before threshold filtering). When the pattern is detected, force-include the position-0 candidate and suppress the ALL_CAPS subtitle.\n    69→\n    70→```typescript\n    71→// BEFORE (lines 385-389):\n    72→const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n    73→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n    74→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    75→\n    76→// AFTER:\n    77→// --- Pre-threshold bilingual title detection ---\n    78→// When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 is followed by a single ALL_CAPS\n    79→// candidate at position ≤ 2 in the FULL scored pool, this is a bilingual recipe\n    80→// page (e.g., Polish title + ALL_CAPS Korean romanization). Suppress the ALL_CAPS\n    81→// candidate before computing threshold so its bonuses don't inflate the threshold\n    82→// beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    83→//\n    84→// This replaces the post-threshold guard at lines 468-479 which was ineffective\n    85→// because it required both candidates to survive threshold independently.\n    86→let scoredForThreshold = scored;\n    87→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n    88→const preAllCaps = scored.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    89→if (\n    90→  prePos0 &&\n    91→  preAllCaps.length === 1 &&\n    92→  preAllCaps[0].position <= 2\n    93→) {\n    94→  // Remove the ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation AND from selection.\n    95→  scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => s !== preAllCaps[0]);\n    96→}\n    97→\n    98→const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scoredForThreshold.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n    99→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n   100→let selected = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n   101→```\n   102→\n   103→Then **remove or disable** the old post-threshold first-line protection (lines 468–479) since it's now redundant.\n   104→\n   105→**Why this is safe:**\n   106→- The guard condition is identical to the old one: mixed-case at position 0, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2.\n   107→- `preAllCaps.length === 1` ensures it never fires on genuine multi-recipe pages (which have ≥ 2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n   108→- Moving it pre-threshold only changes behavior when the mixed-case title would otherwise be below threshold — which is precisely the failure case.\n   109→\n   110→### Expected behavior after fix\n   111→\n   112→- `scored` contains \"Faszerowana papryka\" (pos 0, mixed-case) and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (pos 1, ALL_CAPS).\n   113→- Pre-threshold detection identifies the bilingual pattern: pos0 is mixed-case, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2.\n   114→- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is removed from `scoredForThreshold`.\n   115→- Threshold is now computed from \"Faszerowana papryka\" alone — much lower, achievable.\n   116→- \"Faszerowana papryka\" enters `selected` → returned as the title.\n   117→\n   118→---\n   119→\n   120→## Interaction between the two fixes\n   121→\n   122→The fixes are independent and non-conflicting:\n   123→\n   124→| Scenario | Fix 1 (fallback) | Fix 2 (bilingual) | Which fires? |\n   125→|---|---|---|---|\n   126→| Baked Eggs (sole candidate, below threshold) | Catches it | N/A (no ALL_CAPS) | Fix 1 |\n   127→| Faszerowana papryka (bilingual, threshold inflated) | Would also catch it as fallback | Prevents the problem entirely | Fix 2 (fix 1 is not needed) |\n   128→| Normal recipes (candidates above threshold) | Never fires | Never fires (no pattern match or >1 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n   129→| Multi-recipe ALL_CAPS pages | Never fires (candidates pass threshold) | Never fires (≥2 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n   130→\n   131→Fix 2 is the primary fix for failure 2. Fix 1 is the primary fix for failure 1. But fix 1 would also serve as a secondary safety net for failure 2 if fix 2 somehow didn't fire — defense in depth.\n   132→\n   133→---\n   134→\n   135→## Changes to make (ordered)\n   136→\n   137→### Change 1: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n   138→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   139→**Location:** Before line 385 (threshold computation)\n   140→**Action:** Add bilingual detection on full `scored` array. Suppress the sole ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation and selection when the pattern matches.\n   141→\n   142→### Change 2: Empty-pool fallback\n   143→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   144→**Location:** After line 389 (`let selected = scored.filter(...)`)\n   145→**Action:** Add fallback that selects the best positional candidate when `selected` is empty.\n   146→\n   147→### Change 3: Remove old post-threshold first-line protection\n   148→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   149→**Location:** Lines 468–479\n   150→**Action:** Remove the entire block. It's replaced by the pre-threshold version (change 1) and was ineffective in the failure case anyway.\n   151→\n   152→### No other changes needed\n   153→\n   154→- Hard filters: working correctly for both cases.\n   155→- Pre-merge continuation logic: working correctly (Baked Eggs candidate is correctly merged).\n   156→- Multi-title guard: not involved in either failure.\n   157→- Dedup logic: not involved in either failure.\n   158→- Structural heading detection: not involved in failure 1; correctly identifies PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM in failure 2 but this is handled by the bilingual guard.\n   159→\n   160→---\n   161→\n   162→## Risk Assessment\n   163→\n   164→**Risk of regression on passing tests:**\n   165→- **Low.** Fix 1 (fallback) only fires when `selected` is empty — this never happens for currently-passing tests. Fix 2 (bilingual) only fires when there's a mixed-case pos-0 with exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2 — this pattern doesn't appear in currently-passing tests (they have either 0 or ≥2 ALL_CAPS headings, or no mixed-case at pos 0).\n   166→\n   167→**Risk of over-fitting:**\n   168→- **Moderate but acceptable.** The bilingual guard is specific to a real pattern (bilingual cookbooks) rather than a one-off hack. The empty-pool fallback is a general safety net that addresses a genuine design gap (hard filters should not be overruled by weak embedding signals).\n   169→\n   170→**What could still go wrong:**\n   171→- A recipe where position 0 is genuinely not the title (e.g., book name on first line, recipe title on line 3). The fallback would return the wrong line. Mitigation: this is rare in the test corpus and the hard filters would likely catch book names (too long, or garbled).\n   172→- A recipe where position 0 is mixed-case and position 1 is ALL_CAPS but the ALL_CAPS line is the real title (not a subtitle). The bilingual guard would suppress it. Mitigation: the `position ≤ 2` and `length === 1` constraints are very specific.\n   173→\n   174→## Expected accuracy after changes\n   175→\n   176→- Iteration 8: 75% (6/8 passing, 2 failing)\n   177→- Projected: **100% (8/8 passing)** — both failures addressed with targeted, non-overlapping fixes.\n   178→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fb15cb45-7bdf-4713-bb16-b0fca5051afe","uuid":"5bcc960c-6fd8-4efe-8d1a-73990775e8c6","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/8-b5177f1/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 9 Improvement Plan\n\n## Summary\n\nTwo failures, two distinct root causes that share a common theme: the threshold gate has absolute veto power over candidates that pass all structural/hard filters, with no fallback when the candidate pool is small or the positional signal is unambiguous.\n\nThe fixes are:\n\n1. **Pre-threshold bilingual protection** — move first-line detection before threshold filtering so ALL_CAPS bonuses can't inflate the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n2. **Empty-pool fallback** — when threshold filtering discards every candidate, fall back to the best positional candidate from the hard-filter-passing pool.\n\nThese are complementary: fix 1 prevents failure 2 (Faszerowana papryka) by keeping the correct candidate in `selected`; fix 2 prevents failure 1 (Baked Eggs) by ensuring a sole survivor is never silently discarded.\n\n---\n\n## Failure 1: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" → `''`\n\n### Root Cause\n\nThe pre-merge step correctly produces the full candidate. It passes all hard filters (54 chars, no measurements, no metadata, not garbled). But the embedding scorer computes `rawScore = titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim)` and because ingredient words (Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce, Coriander) are semantically close to `HEADER_REFERENCE` (\"ingredients list, cooking directions\"), `headerSim ≈ titleSim` or `headerSim > titleSim`. The rawScore is near zero or negative. No bonus applies (mixed-case, not structural heading). The final score falls below `threshold = max(0.08, ...)` and the candidate is filtered out, returning `undefined`.\n\nThe fundamental issue: **embeddings cannot distinguish \"dish named after its ingredients\" from \"fragment of an ingredient list\"**. The hard filters already make that distinction (ingredient lists have measurements, start with numbers, etc.), but their verdict is overruled by the embedding threshold.\n\n### Fix: Empty-pool fallback\n\nAfter the existing threshold filter (`let selected = scored.filter(s => s.score >= threshold)`), add a fallback:\n\n```typescript\n// BEFORE (line ~389):\nlet selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n\n// AFTER:\nlet selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n\n// Empty-pool fallback: when threshold filtering discards every candidate,\n// the hard filters' structural verdict should not be overruled by weak\n// embedding differentiation. Return the best positional candidate.\nif (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n  // Prefer candidates near the top of the document (position 0 = most likely title).\n  // Among ties, prefer higher score.\n  const fallback = scored\n    .slice()\n    .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n  selected = [fallback[0]];\n}\n```\n\n**Why this is safe:** Every candidate in `scored` already passed `passesHardFilters()` — no measurements, no metadata, no garbled text, not starting with a number, not lowercase-initial. If the entire pool of structurally-valid candidates has weak embedding differentiation, position is the strongest remaining signal (recipe titles appear at the top of the page). This fallback only fires when `selected` would otherwise be empty, so it cannot degrade any currently-passing test.\n\n### Expected behavior after fix\n\n- \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" is the only candidate in `scored` (the body text, ingredients, and metadata all fail hard filters).\n- Threshold filter discards it (score < 0.08).\n- Fallback selects it as the sole candidate → returns the correct title.\n\n---\n\n## Failure 2: \"Faszerowana papryka\" → `'PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM'`\n\n### Root Cause\n\nThe first-line protection (lines 468–479) was designed for exactly this case: mixed-case title at position 0 followed by ALL_CAPS subtitle. But the protection runs **after** threshold filtering. The ALL_CAPS candidate \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" receives `+0.08` allCapsBonus + `+0.10` structuralBonus = `+0.18` on top of its rawScore. This inflates the threshold via `bestThresholdScore * 0.7`. The Polish mixed-case title \"Faszerowana papryka\" has a low rawScore (MiniLM is English-centric; short Polish text has low cosine similarity to the English TITLE_REFERENCE) and no bonuses. It falls below the inflated threshold, never enters `selected`, and the protection — which checks `selected.find(s => s.position === 0)` — silently becomes a no-op.\n\nThe design is self-defeating: the protection requires the correct title to have already survived the threshold independently, but it's needed precisely when the title **cannot** survive the threshold.\n\n### Fix: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n\nMove the bilingual detection to operate on the full `scored` array (before threshold filtering). When the pattern is detected, force-include the position-0 candidate and suppress the ALL_CAPS subtitle.\n\n```typescript\n// BEFORE (lines 385-389):\nconst bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\nconst threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\nlet selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n\n// AFTER:\n// --- Pre-threshold bilingual title detection ---\n// When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 is followed by a single ALL_CAPS\n// candidate at position ≤ 2 in the FULL scored pool, this is a bilingual recipe\n// page (e.g., Polish title + ALL_CAPS Korean romanization). Suppress the ALL_CAPS\n// candidate before computing threshold so its bonuses don't inflate the threshold\n// beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n//\n// This replaces the post-threshold guard at lines 468-479 which was ineffective\n// because it required both candidates to survive threshold independently.\nlet scoredForThreshold = scored;\nconst prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\nconst preAllCaps = scored.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\nif (\n  prePos0 &&\n  preAllCaps.length === 1 &&\n  preAllCaps[0].position <= 2\n) {\n  // Remove the ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation AND from selection.\n  scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => s !== preAllCaps[0]);\n}\n\nconst bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scoredForThreshold.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\nconst threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\nlet selected = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n```\n\nThen **remove or disable** the old post-threshold first-line protection (lines 468–479) since it's now redundant.\n\n**Why this is safe:**\n- The guard condition is identical to the old one: mixed-case at position 0, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2.\n- `preAllCaps.length === 1` ensures it never fires on genuine multi-recipe pages (which have ≥ 2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n- Moving it pre-threshold only changes behavior when the mixed-case title would otherwise be below threshold — which is precisely the failure case.\n\n### Expected behavior after fix\n\n- `scored` contains \"Faszerowana papryka\" (pos 0, mixed-case) and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (pos 1, ALL_CAPS).\n- Pre-threshold detection identifies the bilingual pattern: pos0 is mixed-case, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2.\n- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is removed from `scoredForThreshold`.\n- Threshold is now computed from \"Faszerowana papryka\" alone — much lower, achievable.\n- \"Faszerowana papryka\" enters `selected` → returned as the title.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction between the two fixes\n\nThe fixes are independent and non-conflicting:\n\n| Scenario | Fix 1 (fallback) | Fix 2 (bilingual) | Which fires? |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Baked Eggs (sole candidate, below threshold) | Catches it | N/A (no ALL_CAPS) | Fix 1 |\n| Faszerowana papryka (bilingual, threshold inflated) | Would also catch it as fallback | Prevents the problem entirely | Fix 2 (fix 1 is not needed) |\n| Normal recipes (candidates above threshold) | Never fires | Never fires (no pattern match or >1 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n| Multi-recipe ALL_CAPS pages | Never fires (candidates pass threshold) | Never fires (≥2 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n\nFix 2 is the primary fix for failure 2. Fix 1 is the primary fix for failure 1. But fix 1 would also serve as a secondary safety net for failure 2 if fix 2 somehow didn't fire — defense in depth.\n\n---\n\n## Changes to make (ordered)\n\n### Change 1: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n**Location:** Before line 385 (threshold computation)\n**Action:** Add bilingual detection on full `scored` array. Suppress the sole ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation and selection when the pattern matches.\n\n### Change 2: Empty-pool fallback\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n**Location:** After line 389 (`let selected = scored.filter(...)`)\n**Action:** Add fallback that selects the best positional candidate when `selected` is empty.\n\n### Change 3: Remove old post-threshold first-line protection\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n**Location:** Lines 468–479\n**Action:** Remove the entire block. It's replaced by the pre-threshold version (change 1) and was ineffective in the failure case anyway.\n\n### No other changes needed\n\n- Hard filters: working correctly for both cases.\n- Pre-merge continuation logic: working correctly (Baked Eggs candidate is correctly merged).\n- Multi-title guard: not involved in either failure.\n- Dedup logic: not involved in either failure.\n- Structural heading detection: not involved in failure 1; correctly identifies PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM in failure 2 but this is handled by the bilingual guard.\n\n---\n\n## Risk Assessment\n\n**Risk of regression on passing tests:**\n- **Low.** Fix 1 (fallback) only fires when `selected` is empty — this never happens for currently-passing tests. Fix 2 (bilingual) only fires when there's a mixed-case pos-0 with exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2 — this pattern doesn't appear in currently-passing tests (they have either 0 or ≥2 ALL_CAPS headings, or no mixed-case at pos 0).\n\n**Risk of over-fitting:**\n- **Moderate but acceptable.** The bilingual guard is specific to a real pattern (bilingual cookbooks) rather than a one-off hack. The empty-pool fallback is a general safety net that addresses a genuine design gap (hard filters should not be overruled by weak embedding signals).\n\n**What could still go wrong:**\n- A recipe where position 0 is genuinely not the title (e.g., book name on first line, recipe title on line 3). The fallback would return the wrong line. Mitigation: this is rare in the test corpus and the hard filters would likely catch book names (too long, or garbled).\n- A recipe where position 0 is mixed-case and position 1 is ALL_CAPS but the ALL_CAPS line is the real title (not a subtitle). The bilingual guard would suppress it. Mitigation: the `position ≤ 2` and `length === 1` constraints are very specific.\n\n## Expected accuracy after changes\n\n- Iteration 8: 75% (6/8 passing, 2 failing)\n- Projected: **100% (8/8 passing)** — both failures addressed with targeted, non-overlapping fixes.\n","numLines":178,"startLine":1,"totalLines":178}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KCb1TKSxmW61s3xPEQx6PJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * Title Extraction\n     3→ * Extracts potential recipe title from OCR text using heuristics or semantic embeddings\n     4→ */\n     5→\n     6→import { cosineSimilarity } from \"./embeddings\";\n     7→\n     8→export type EmbedFn = (text: string) => Promise<Array<number>>;\n     9→\n    10→const TITLE_REFERENCE =\n    11→  \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food, nazwa przepisu, nazwa dania\";\n    12→const HEADER_REFERENCE =\n    13→  \"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading, składniki, przygotowanie, sposób wykonania\";\n    14→const NOISE_REFERENCE =\n    15→  \"page number, table of contents, book footer, garbled text\";\n    16→\n    17→/**\n    18→ * Measurement units commonly found in ingredient lists\n    19→ */\n    20→const MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS = [\n    21→  \"cup\",\n    22→  \"cups\",\n    23→  \"tbsp\",\n    24→  \"tsp\",\n    25→  \"tablespoon\",\n    26→  \"teaspoon\",\n    27→  \"oz\",\n    28→  \"lb\",\n    29→  \"gram\",\n    30→  \"grams\",\n    31→  \"kg\",\n    32→  \"ml\",\n    33→  \"liter\",\n    34→  \"pinch\",\n    35→  \"dash\",\n    36→  \"handful\",\n    37→];\n    38→\n    39→/**\n    40→ * Patterns that identify recipe metadata lines (not titles)\n    41→ */\n    42→const METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n    43→  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n    44→  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n    45→  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n    46→  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n    47→  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n    48→];\n    49→\n    50→/**\n    51→ * Single-word non-title words — standalone OCR fragments unlikely to be recipe titles\n    52→ */\n    53→const NON_TITLE_WORDS = new Set([\n    54→  \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"are\", \"was\",\n    55→  \"has\", \"his\", \"her\", \"its\", \"our\", \"who\", \"how\", \"may\", \"new\", \"now\",\n    56→  \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\", \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n    57→  \"buns\", \"with\",\n    58→]);\n    59→\n    60→function looksLikeIngredient(line: string): boolean {\n    61→  const lowerLine = line.toLowerCase();\n    62→  return MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => lowerLine.includes(pattern));\n    63→}\n    64→\n    65→function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n    66→  return /^\\s*\\d/.test(line);\n    67→}\n    68→\n    69→function isAllCaps(line: string): boolean {\n    70→  const letters = line.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n    71→  return letters.length > 0 && letters === letters.toUpperCase();\n    72→}\n    73→\n    74→function looksLikeMetadata(text: string): boolean {\n    75→  return METADATA_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(text.trim()));\n    76→}\n    77→\n    78→function isLikelyGarbled(text: string): boolean {\n    79→  const letters = text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n    80→  if (letters.length < 2) return true;\n    81→\n    82→  // Check vowel ratio — English/Polish text typically has 30–50% vowels\n    83→  const vowels = letters.replace(/[^aeiouAEIOUyYąęóĄĘÓ]/g, \"\").length;\n    84→  const vowelRatio = vowels / letters.length;\n    85→  if (vowelRatio < 0.15 || vowelRatio > 0.85) return true;\n    86→\n    87→  // Single orphaned word ≤3 letters that isn't a common word\n    88→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    89→  const COMMON_SHORT = new Set([\n    90→    \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"had\", \"her\",\n    91→    \"was\", \"one\", \"our\", \"out\", \"are\", \"has\", \"his\", \"how\", \"its\", \"may\",\n    92→    \"new\", \"now\", \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"who\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\",\n    93→    \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n    94→  ]);\n    95→  if (words.length === 1 && letters.length <= 3 && !COMMON_SHORT.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) {\n    96→    return true;\n    97→  }\n    98→\n    99→  // Recipe titles never start with a lowercase letter\n   100→  if (/^[a-z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n   101→    return true;\n   102→  }\n   103→\n   104→  // Mid-text sentence boundary (\". \" followed by a letter) — body text fragment spliced from multiple sentences\n   105→  const trimmed = text.trim();\n   106→  if (/\\.\\s+[a-zA-Z]/.test(trimmed) && !trimmed.endsWith(\")\")) {\n   107→    return true;\n   108→  }\n   109→\n   110→  // Multi-word candidate containing a garbled OCR fragment: a short lowercase word that isn't a known short word\n   111→  if (words.length >= 2) {\n   112→    const commonShort2 = new Set([\n   113→      \"a\", \"i\", \"of\", \"or\", \"to\", \"in\", \"on\", \"is\", \"it\", \"an\",\n   114→      \"as\", \"at\", \"by\", \"do\", \"go\", \"if\", \"no\", \"so\", \"up\", \"we\",\n   115→      \"w\", \"z\",  // Polish prepositions\n   116→    ]);\n   117→    const hasGarbledWord = words.some(\n   118→      (w) =>\n   119→        /^[a-z]/.test(w) &&\n   120→        w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2 &&\n   121→        !commonShort2.has(w.toLowerCase())\n   122→    );\n   123→    if (hasGarbledWord) {\n   124→      return true;\n   125→    }\n   126→  }\n   127→\n   128→  return false;\n   129→}\n   130→\n   131→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n   132→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n   133→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n   134→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n   135→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n   136→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n   137→  // Single-word non-title fragments\n   138→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   139→  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n   140→  return true;\n   141→}\n   142→\n   143→/**\n   144→ * Detect initial burst of short garbled lines.\n   145→ * Returns the index of the first non-garbled or long line.\n   146→ */\n   147→function findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\n   148→  let i = 0;\n   149→  while (i < lines.length && lines[i].text.length < 20 && isLikelyGarbled(lines[i].text)) {\n   150→    i++;\n   151→  }\n   152→  return i;\n   153→}\n   154→\n   155→function wordCount(text: string): number {\n   156→  return text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.length > 0).length;\n   157→}\n   158→\n   159→/**\n   160→ * Build candidate strings from lines: single lines plus multi-line joins (2-3 consecutive).\n   161→ * Skips initial burst of short garbled lines. Scans all remaining lines. Caps at 25.\n   162→ */\n   163→export type CandidateOrigin = \"single\" | \"2-line\" | \"3-line\";\n   164→\n   165→function buildCandidates(\n   166→  lines: Array<string>\n   167→): Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> {\n   168→  const nonEmptyLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n   169→\n   170→  for (let i = 0; i < lines.length; i++) {\n   171→    const trimmed = lines[i].trim();\n   172→    if (trimmed.length > 0) {\n   173→      nonEmptyLines.push({ text: trimmed, index: i });\n   174→    }\n   175→  }\n   176→\n   177→  const burstEnd = findBurstEnd(nonEmptyLines);\n   178→\n   179→  // Pre-merge continuation lines: a line starting with /&+:( is never a standalone title.\n   180→  // Merge it into the preceding line so the complete title enters the pool as a single candidate,\n   181→  // avoiding the fragile chain of conditions required by the downstream join survival logic.\n   182→  // Limitation: only one continuation line per preceding line is merged. Titles split across\n   183→  // three or more lines with continuation tokens (rare in practice) are not handled here —\n   184→  // the downstream 2-line and 3-line join candidates cover those cases instead.\n   185→  const mergedLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n   186→  for (let i = burstEnd; i < nonEmptyLines.length; i++) {\n   187→    const line = nonEmptyLines[i];\n   188→    if (i + 1 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n   189→      const nextText = nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text;\n   190→      if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n   191→        mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n   192→        i++;\n   193→        continue;\n   194→      }\n   195→    }\n   196→    mergedLines.push(line);\n   197→  }\n   198→\n   199→  const candidates: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> = [];\n   200→  const seen = new Set<string>();\n   201→\n   202→  for (let i = 0; i < mergedLines.length; i++) {\n   203→    const line = mergedLines[i];\n   204→\n   205→    // Single line\n   206→    if (passesHardFilters(line.text)) {\n   207→      const norm = line.text.toLowerCase();\n   208→      if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   209→        seen.add(norm);\n   210→        candidates.push({ text: line.text, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n   211→      }\n   212→    }\n   213→\n   214→    // 2-line join\n   215→    if (i + 1 < mergedLines.length) {\n   216→      const joined2 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text}`;\n   217→      if (passesHardFilters(joined2)) {\n   218→        const norm = joined2.toLowerCase();\n   219→        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   220→          seen.add(norm);\n   221→          candidates.push({ text: joined2, position: line.index, origin: \"2-line\" });\n   222→        }\n   223→      }\n   224→    }\n   225→\n   226→    // 3-line join\n   227→    if (i + 2 < mergedLines.length) {\n   228→      const joined3 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text} ${mergedLines[i + 2].text}`;\n   229→      if (passesHardFilters(joined3)) {\n   230→        const norm = joined3.toLowerCase();\n   231→        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   232→          seen.add(norm);\n   233→          candidates.push({ text: joined3, position: line.index, origin: \"3-line\" });\n   234→        }\n   235→      }\n   236→    }\n   237→  }\n   238→\n   239→  // Pre-filter to 25 before embedding calls: prefer ALL_CAPS and short candidates.\n   240→  // Position-based scoring handles final ranking.\n   241→  if (candidates.length > 25) {\n   242→    const prioritized = candidates.slice().sort((a, b) => {\n   243→      const aAllCaps = isAllCaps(a.text) ? 0 : 1;\n   244→      const bAllCaps = isAllCaps(b.text) ? 0 : 1;\n   245→      if (aAllCaps !== bAllCaps) return aAllCaps - bAllCaps;\n   246→      const aShort = wordCount(a.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n   247→      const bShort = wordCount(b.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n   248→      return aShort - bShort;\n   249→    });\n   250→    return prioritized.slice(0, 25);\n   251→  }\n   252→\n   253→  return candidates;\n   254→}\n   255→\n   256→// Module-level cache for reference embeddings\n   257→let cachedTitleRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   258→let cachedHeaderRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   259→let cachedNoiseRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   260→\n   261→export function _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests(): void {\n   262→  cachedTitleRefEmbedding = null;\n   263→  cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = null;\n   264→  cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = null;\n   265→}\n   266→\n   267→export async function extractTitleWithEmbeddings(\n   268→  text: string,\n   269→  embed: EmbedFn\n   270→): Promise<string | undefined> {\n   271→  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n   272→    return undefined;\n   273→  }\n   274→\n   275→  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\");\n   276→  const candidates = buildCandidates(lines);\n   277→\n   278→  if (candidates.length === 0) {\n   279→    return undefined;\n   280→  }\n   281→\n   282→  // Cache reference embeddings\n   283→  if (!cachedTitleRefEmbedding) {\n   284→    cachedTitleRefEmbedding = await embed(TITLE_REFERENCE);\n   285→  }\n   286→  if (!cachedHeaderRefEmbedding) {\n   287→    cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = await embed(HEADER_REFERENCE);\n   288→  }\n   289→  if (!cachedNoiseRefEmbedding) {\n   290→    cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = await embed(NOISE_REFERENCE);\n   291→  }\n   292→\n   293→  // Find ALL_CAPS candidates with ≥2 words where every significant word has ≥4 alpha letters.\n   294→  // Insignificant tokens (≤1 alpha letter: \"/\", \"&\", \"+\", \":\", \"D)\", etc.) are filtered before\n   295→  // the check so that multi-line joins with continuation punctuation still qualify.\n   296→  const isStructuralHeading = (c: { text: string }): boolean => {\n   297→    if (!isAllCaps(c.text) || wordCount(c.text) < 2) return false;\n   298→    const sigWords = c.text.trim().split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length > 1);\n   299→    return sigWords.length >= 2 && sigWords.every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   300→  };\n   301→\n   302→  // Pass 1: compute rawScore for all candidates (embedding quality signal)\n   303→  const rawScored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; rawScore: number; embedding: Array<number> }> = [];\n   304→  for (const candidate of candidates) {\n   305→    const embedding = await embed(candidate.text);\n   306→    const titleSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedTitleRefEmbedding);\n   307→    const headerSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedHeaderRefEmbedding);\n   308→    const noiseSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedNoiseRefEmbedding);\n   309→    const rawScore = titleSim - Math.max(headerSim, noiseSim);\n   310→    rawScored.push({ text: candidate.text, position: candidate.position, origin: candidate.origin, rawScore, embedding });\n   311→  }\n   312→\n   313→  // Select baseHeading by embedding quality (rawScore), not position.\n   314→  // This prevents OCR-garbled fragments from claiming the structural heading slot.\n   315→  const structuralCandidates = rawScored.filter((s) => isStructuralHeading(s));\n   316→\n   317→  // Penalize structural headings with truncated OCR words:\n   318→  // if \"FRON\" appears and another heading has \"SAFFRON\", \"FRON\" is likely garbled.\n   319→  for (const sc of structuralCandidates) {\n   320→    const sigWords = sc.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   321→    for (const other of structuralCandidates) {\n   322→      if (other === sc) continue;\n   323→      const otherSigWords = other.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   324→      const hasTruncation = sigWords.some((w) =>\n   325→        otherSigWords.some((ow) => ow !== w && ow.length > w.length && ow.endsWith(w))\n   326→      );\n   327→      if (hasTruncation) {\n   328→        sc.rawScore = -1.0;  // Hard disqualification — truncated OCR artifact\n   329→        break;\n   330→      }\n   331→    }\n   332→  }\n   333→\n   334→  const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n   335→    ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n   336→    : null;\n   337→  const baseHeading = bestStructural ?? undefined;\n   338→\n   339→  // When the best structural heading has a continuation on the next line introduced by a\n   340→  // punctuation token (/, &, +, :, or parenthesis), prefer the longer 2-line join as the\n   341→  // complete heading. E.g. \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" + \"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\".\n   342→  // Guard: the remainder after the prefix must start with a continuation character to avoid\n   343→  // merging two separate consecutive recipe titles (FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS stays separate\n   344→  // from FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS because \"FINNISH\" does not start with a continuation token).\n   345→  const firstStructuralHeading = baseHeading && (\n   346→    rawScored.find((c) => {\n   347→      if (!isStructuralHeading(c)) return false;\n   348→      const hLower = baseHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n   349→      const cLower = c.text.toLowerCase();\n   350→      return cLower.startsWith(hLower + \" \") && /^[/&+:(]/.test(cLower.slice(hLower.length + 1));\n   351→    }) ?? baseHeading\n   352→  );\n   353→\n   354→  // Pass 2: apply bonuses\n   355→  const scored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; score: number; rawScore: number; baseScore: number; thresholdScore: number }> = rawScored.map((rs) => {\n   356→    // Position factor: multiplicative tiebreaker — amplifies existing signal, doesn't replace it\n   357→    const relativePosition = rs.position / lines.length;\n   358→    const positionFactor = relativePosition < 0.5\n   359→      ? 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - relativePosition * 2)\n   360→      : 1.0;\n   361→\n   362→    // ALL_CAPS bonus: recipe books use ALL_CAPS for titles and section headings\n   363→    const allCapsBonus = isAllCaps(rs.text) && rs.text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4\n   364→      ? 0.08\n   365→      : 0;\n   366→\n   367→    // Structural heading bonus: best ALL_CAPS heading (or its continuation join) is almost always the recipe title\n   368→    const structuralBonus = firstStructuralHeading && rs.text === firstStructuralHeading.text ? 0.10 : 0;\n   369→\n   370→    // thresholdScore excludes structural bonus so the bonus doesn't inflate the threshold\n   371→    // and prevent equally-valid structural headings from passing on multi-recipe pages.\n   372→    const thresholdScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus;\n   373→    // baseScore excludes position factor — used for diagnostics and ranking\n   374→    const baseScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   375→    const score = rs.rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   376→    return { text: rs.text, position: rs.position, origin: rs.origin, score, rawScore: rs.rawScore, baseScore, thresholdScore };\n   377→  });\n   378→\n   379→  if (scored.length === 0) {\n   380→    return undefined;\n   381→  }\n   382→\n   383→  // Use thresholdScore (excludes structural bonus) so the structural bonus doesn't inflate\n   384→  // the threshold and block equally-valid headings on multi-recipe pages.\n   385→  const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n   386→  const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n   387→\n   388→  // Filter candidates above threshold\n   389→  let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n   390→\n   391→  // Remove word-boundary prefixes of firstStructuralHeading when the heading itself survived\n   392→  // the threshold. Cases:\n   393→  //   ARAYES case:  firstStructuralHeading = \"ARAYES SHRAK\" (2-word join qualifies; \"ARAYES\"\n   394→  //     alone = 1 word, so it never qualified). Filter removes \"ARAYES\" so dedup keeps the join.\n   395→  //   SAFFRON case: baseHeading was the partial line; continuation logic above upgraded\n   396→  //     firstStructuralHeading to the full join. Filter removes the partial so dedup keeps join.\n   397→  // Safety: only fires when the complete heading itself is in selected (passed the threshold).\n   398→  if (firstStructuralHeading && selected.some((s) => s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text)) {\n   399→    const fshLower = firstStructuralHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n   400→    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n   401→      if (s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text) return true;\n   402→      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   403→      // Remove s if it is a space-delimited prefix of the structural heading\n   404→      return !fshLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \");\n   405→    });\n   406→  }\n   407→\n   408→  // Protect continuation joins: when a multi-line join (2-line or 3-line) survived the threshold\n   409→  // and its second part starts with a continuation character, remove the single-line prefix/suffix\n   410→  // so the dedup \"shorter wins\" rule doesn't destroy the complete join.\n   411→  // Note: the pre-merge step above already handles the common Baked Eggs case (&/continuation\n   412→  // on next line) by turning it into a single candidate — this block covers the rarer case where\n   413→  // a continuation-character join was generated as a 2-line/3-line candidate and the prefix\n   414→  // single also survived threshold independently (e.g. from a different code path or OCR layout).\n   415→  // Safety: only fires for joins whose continuation starts with /&+:( — digit continuations\n   416→  // like \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki\" are NOT protected, so dedup correctly keeps the shorter form.\n   417→  const survivingJoins = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n   418→  if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n   419→    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n   420→      if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n   421→      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   422→      // Remove PREFIX singles whose continuation join also survived\n   423→      const isPrefixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   424→        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   425→        if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n   426→        const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n   427→        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n   428→      });\n   429→      if (isPrefixOfJoin) return false;\n   430→      // Remove SUFFIX singles (e.g. \"& Coriander\") whose parent join also survived\n   431→      const isSuffixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   432→        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   433→        if (!jLower.endsWith(\" \" + sLower)) return false;\n   434→        // Only remove if the suffix starts with a continuation character\n   435→        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(sLower);\n   436→      });\n   437→      if (isSuffixOfJoin) return false;\n   438→      return true;\n   439→    });\n   440→  }\n   441→\n   442→  // Deduplicate: if one title is a substring of another, keep the shorter (more focused) one.\n   443→  // DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC — it has been incorrectly \"improved\" by the title-loop 5 times.\n   444→  // The tests require shorter wins: \"Pierogi Ruskie\" over \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\".\n   445→  // The pre-filter above handles the conflicting case (structural heading prefix removal) so that\n   446→  // the incomplete prefix line is never present here when the complete join is in selected.\n   447→  selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n   448→    const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n   449→    return !selected.some(\n   450→      (b) =>\n   451→        b !== a &&\n   452→        aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) &&\n   453→        b.text.length < a.text.length\n   454→    );\n   455→  });\n   456→\n   457→  // First-line mixed-case title protection:\n   458→  // When a mixed-case title at position 0 has a reasonable score and the only ALL_CAPS\n   459→  // candidate is at position ≤ 2 (i.e. within the first two non-empty document lines,\n   460→  // allowing for one blank line between title and subtitle), treat the ALL_CAPS line as a\n   461→  // subtitle/transliteration and prefer the first-line title. This handles bilingual cookbooks\n   462→  // where the primary-language title precedes an ALL_CAPS romanization.\n   463→  // Placement: runs AFTER dedup (so both candidates were already compared for substring overlap)\n   464→  // but BEFORE the multi-title guard (so the guard never sees the removed subtitle as a\n   465→  // candidate that could collapse the selection to the wrong winner).\n   466→  // Safety: allCapsCandidates.length === 1 ensures the guard never fires on genuine multi-recipe\n   467→  // pages (which have ≥ 2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n   468→  if (selected.length >= 1) {\n   469→    const pos0 = selected.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n   470→    const allCapsCandidates = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n   471→    if (\n   472→      pos0 &&\n   473→      allCapsCandidates.length === 1 &&\n   474→      allCapsCandidates[0].position <= 2 &&\n   475→      pos0.score >= threshold\n   476→    ) {\n   477→      selected = selected.filter((s) => s !== allCapsCandidates[0]);\n   478→    }\n   479→  }\n   480→\n   481→  // Multi-title guard: only join multiple candidates with \"+\" when there is\n   482→  // structural evidence of a multi-recipe page (≥2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n   483→  // A single ALL_CAPS title among mixed-case survivors is a single-recipe page —\n   484→  // collapse to the highest-scoring candidate.\n   485→  // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → mixed-case multi-title page → keep all.\n   486→  if (selected.length > 1) {\n   487→    const allCapsSelected = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n   488→    if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n   489→      // Check whether non-first ALL_CAPS headings are section headers within one recipe\n   490→      // (followed immediately by ingredient-like content) rather than separate recipe titles.\n   491→      // A multi-recipe page has body text between titles; a single-recipe page has\n   492→      // ingredient lines immediately after each section heading.\n   493→      const sortedCaps = [...allCapsSelected].sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   494→      const isSubHeader = sortedCaps.slice(1).every((cap) => {\n   495→        const nextLines = lines.slice(cap.position + 1, cap.position + 3);\n   496→        return nextLines.some(\n   497→          (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   498→        );\n   499→      });\n   500→      if (isSubHeader) {\n   501→        selected = [sortedCaps[0]];\n   502→      } else {\n   503→        selected = allCapsSelected;\n   504→      }\n   505→    } else if (allCapsSelected.length === 1) {\n   506→      selected = [selected.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))];\n   507→    }\n   508→  }\n   509→\n   510→  // Cap at 3, sort by document position\n   511→  selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   512→  selected = selected.slice(0, 3);\n   513→\n   514→  if (selected.length === 0) {\n   515→    return undefined;\n   516→  }\n   517→\n   518→  return selected.map((s) => s.text).join(\" + \");\n   519→}\n   520→\n   521→/**\n   522→ * Extract potential recipe title from OCR text (sync heuristic fallback)\n   523→ */\n   524→export function extractTitle(text: string): string | undefined {\n   525→  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n   526→    return undefined;\n   527→  }\n   528→\n   529→  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\").map((line) => line.trim());\n   530→\n   531→  for (const line of lines) {\n   532→    if (line.length === 0) continue;\n   533→    if (line.length < 3 || line.length > 50) continue;\n   534→    if (looksLikeIngredient(line)) continue;\n   535→    if (isAllCaps(line)) continue;\n   536→    if (startsWithNumber(line)) continue;\n   537→    return line;\n   538→  }\n   539→\n   540→  return undefined;\n   541→}\n   542→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fb15cb45-7bdf-4713-bb16-b0fca5051afe","uuid":"0533b705-cb9b-4e30-b5c2-fefaf676aead","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts","content":"/**\n * Title Extraction\n * Extracts potential recipe title from OCR text using heuristics or semantic embeddings\n */\n\nimport { cosineSimilarity } from \"./embeddings\";\n\nexport type EmbedFn = (text: string) => Promise<Array<number>>;\n\nconst TITLE_REFERENCE =\n  \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food, nazwa przepisu, nazwa dania\";\nconst HEADER_REFERENCE =\n  \"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading, składniki, przygotowanie, sposób wykonania\";\nconst NOISE_REFERENCE =\n  \"page number, table of contents, book footer, garbled text\";\n\n/**\n * Measurement units commonly found in ingredient lists\n */\nconst MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS = [\n  \"cup\",\n  \"cups\",\n  \"tbsp\",\n  \"tsp\",\n  \"tablespoon\",\n  \"teaspoon\",\n  \"oz\",\n  \"lb\",\n  \"gram\",\n  \"grams\",\n  \"kg\",\n  \"ml\",\n  \"liter\",\n  \"pinch\",\n  \"dash\",\n  \"handful\",\n];\n\n/**\n * Patterns that identify recipe metadata lines (not titles)\n */\nconst METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n];\n\n/**\n * Single-word non-title words — standalone OCR fragments unlikely to be recipe titles\n */\nconst NON_TITLE_WORDS = new Set([\n  \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"are\", \"was\",\n  \"has\", \"his\", \"her\", \"its\", \"our\", \"who\", \"how\", \"may\", \"new\", \"now\",\n  \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\", \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n  \"buns\", \"with\",\n]);\n\nfunction looksLikeIngredient(line: string): boolean {\n  const lowerLine = line.toLowerCase();\n  return MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => lowerLine.includes(pattern));\n}\n\nfunction startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n  return /^\\s*\\d/.test(line);\n}\n\nfunction isAllCaps(line: string): boolean {\n  const letters = line.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n  return letters.length > 0 && letters === letters.toUpperCase();\n}\n\nfunction looksLikeMetadata(text: string): boolean {\n  return METADATA_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(text.trim()));\n}\n\nfunction isLikelyGarbled(text: string): boolean {\n  const letters = text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n  if (letters.length < 2) return true;\n\n  // Check vowel ratio — English/Polish text typically has 30–50% vowels\n  const vowels = letters.replace(/[^aeiouAEIOUyYąęóĄĘÓ]/g, \"\").length;\n  const vowelRatio = vowels / letters.length;\n  if (vowelRatio < 0.15 || vowelRatio > 0.85) return true;\n\n  // Single orphaned word ≤3 letters that isn't a common word\n  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n  const COMMON_SHORT = new Set([\n    \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"had\", \"her\",\n    \"was\", \"one\", \"our\", \"out\", \"are\", \"has\", \"his\", \"how\", \"its\", \"may\",\n    \"new\", \"now\", \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"who\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\",\n    \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n  ]);\n  if (words.length === 1 && letters.length <= 3 && !COMMON_SHORT.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  // Recipe titles never start with a lowercase letter\n  if (/^[a-z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  // Mid-text sentence boundary (\". \" followed by a letter) — body text fragment spliced from multiple sentences\n  const trimmed = text.trim();\n  if (/\\.\\s+[a-zA-Z]/.test(trimmed) && !trimmed.endsWith(\")\")) {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  // Multi-word candidate containing a garbled OCR fragment: a short lowercase word that isn't a known short word\n  if (words.length >= 2) {\n    const commonShort2 = new Set([\n      \"a\", \"i\", \"of\", \"or\", \"to\", \"in\", \"on\", \"is\", \"it\", \"an\",\n      \"as\", \"at\", \"by\", \"do\", \"go\", \"if\", \"no\", \"so\", \"up\", \"we\",\n      \"w\", \"z\",  // Polish prepositions\n    ]);\n    const hasGarbledWord = words.some(\n      (w) =>\n        /^[a-z]/.test(w) &&\n        w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2 &&\n        !commonShort2.has(w.toLowerCase())\n    );\n    if (hasGarbledWord) {\n      return true;\n    }\n  }\n\n  return false;\n}\n\nfunction passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n  // Single-word non-title fragments\n  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n  return true;\n}\n\n/**\n * Detect initial burst of short garbled lines.\n * Returns the index of the first non-garbled or long line.\n */\nfunction findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\n  let i = 0;\n  while (i < lines.length && lines[i].text.length < 20 && isLikelyGarbled(lines[i].text)) {\n    i++;\n  }\n  return i;\n}\n\nfunction wordCount(text: string): number {\n  return text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.length > 0).length;\n}\n\n/**\n * Build candidate strings from lines: single lines plus multi-line joins (2-3 consecutive).\n * Skips initial burst of short garbled lines. Scans all remaining lines. Caps at 25.\n */\nexport type CandidateOrigin = \"single\" | \"2-line\" | \"3-line\";\n\nfunction buildCandidates(\n  lines: Array<string>\n): Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> {\n  const nonEmptyLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n\n  for (let i = 0; i < lines.length; i++) {\n    const trimmed = lines[i].trim();\n    if (trimmed.length > 0) {\n      nonEmptyLines.push({ text: trimmed, index: i });\n    }\n  }\n\n  const burstEnd = findBurstEnd(nonEmptyLines);\n\n  // Pre-merge continuation lines: a line starting with /&+:( is never a standalone title.\n  // Merge it into the preceding line so the complete title enters the pool as a single candidate,\n  // avoiding the fragile chain of conditions required by the downstream join survival logic.\n  // Limitation: only one continuation line per preceding line is merged. Titles split across\n  // three or more lines with continuation tokens (rare in practice) are not handled here —\n  // the downstream 2-line and 3-line join candidates cover those cases instead.\n  const mergedLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n  for (let i = burstEnd; i < nonEmptyLines.length; i++) {\n    const line = nonEmptyLines[i];\n    if (i + 1 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n      const nextText = nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text;\n      if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n        mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n        i++;\n        continue;\n      }\n    }\n    mergedLines.push(line);\n  }\n\n  const candidates: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> = [];\n  const seen = new Set<string>();\n\n  for (let i = 0; i < mergedLines.length; i++) {\n    const line = mergedLines[i];\n\n    // Single line\n    if (passesHardFilters(line.text)) {\n      const norm = line.text.toLowerCase();\n      if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n        seen.add(norm);\n        candidates.push({ text: line.text, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n      }\n    }\n\n    // 2-line join\n    if (i + 1 < mergedLines.length) {\n      const joined2 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text}`;\n      if (passesHardFilters(joined2)) {\n        const norm = joined2.toLowerCase();\n        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n          seen.add(norm);\n          candidates.push({ text: joined2, position: line.index, origin: \"2-line\" });\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // 3-line join\n    if (i + 2 < mergedLines.length) {\n      const joined3 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text} ${mergedLines[i + 2].text}`;\n      if (passesHardFilters(joined3)) {\n        const norm = joined3.toLowerCase();\n        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n          seen.add(norm);\n          candidates.push({ text: joined3, position: line.index, origin: \"3-line\" });\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Pre-filter to 25 before embedding calls: prefer ALL_CAPS and short candidates.\n  // Position-based scoring handles final ranking.\n  if (candidates.length > 25) {\n    const prioritized = candidates.slice().sort((a, b) => {\n      const aAllCaps = isAllCaps(a.text) ? 0 : 1;\n      const bAllCaps = isAllCaps(b.text) ? 0 : 1;\n      if (aAllCaps !== bAllCaps) return aAllCaps - bAllCaps;\n      const aShort = wordCount(a.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n      const bShort = wordCount(b.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n      return aShort - bShort;\n    });\n    return prioritized.slice(0, 25);\n  }\n\n  return candidates;\n}\n\n// Module-level cache for reference embeddings\nlet cachedTitleRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\nlet cachedHeaderRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\nlet cachedNoiseRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n\nexport function _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests(): void {\n  cachedTitleRefEmbedding = null;\n  cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = null;\n  cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = null;\n}\n\nexport async function extractTitleWithEmbeddings(\n  text: string,\n  embed: EmbedFn\n): Promise<string | undefined> {\n  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\");\n  const candidates = buildCandidates(lines);\n\n  if (candidates.length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  // Cache reference embeddings\n  if (!cachedTitleRefEmbedding) {\n    cachedTitleRefEmbedding = await embed(TITLE_REFERENCE);\n  }\n  if (!cachedHeaderRefEmbedding) {\n    cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = await embed(HEADER_REFERENCE);\n  }\n  if (!cachedNoiseRefEmbedding) {\n    cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = await embed(NOISE_REFERENCE);\n  }\n\n  // Find ALL_CAPS candidates with ≥2 words where every significant word has ≥4 alpha letters.\n  // Insignificant tokens (≤1 alpha letter: \"/\", \"&\", \"+\", \":\", \"D)\", etc.) are filtered before\n  // the check so that multi-line joins with continuation punctuation still qualify.\n  const isStructuralHeading = (c: { text: string }): boolean => {\n    if (!isAllCaps(c.text) || wordCount(c.text) < 2) return false;\n    const sigWords = c.text.trim().split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length > 1);\n    return sigWords.length >= 2 && sigWords.every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n  };\n\n  // Pass 1: compute rawScore for all candidates (embedding quality signal)\n  const rawScored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; rawScore: number; embedding: Array<number> }> = [];\n  for (const candidate of candidates) {\n    const embedding = await embed(candidate.text);\n    const titleSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedTitleRefEmbedding);\n    const headerSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedHeaderRefEmbedding);\n    const noiseSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedNoiseRefEmbedding);\n    const rawScore = titleSim - Math.max(headerSim, noiseSim);\n    rawScored.push({ text: candidate.text, position: candidate.position, origin: candidate.origin, rawScore, embedding });\n  }\n\n  // Select baseHeading by embedding quality (rawScore), not position.\n  // This prevents OCR-garbled fragments from claiming the structural heading slot.\n  const structuralCandidates = rawScored.filter((s) => isStructuralHeading(s));\n\n  // Penalize structural headings with truncated OCR words:\n  // if \"FRON\" appears and another heading has \"SAFFRON\", \"FRON\" is likely garbled.\n  for (const sc of structuralCandidates) {\n    const sigWords = sc.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n    for (const other of structuralCandidates) {\n      if (other === sc) continue;\n      const otherSigWords = other.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n      const hasTruncation = sigWords.some((w) =>\n        otherSigWords.some((ow) => ow !== w && ow.length > w.length && ow.endsWith(w))\n      );\n      if (hasTruncation) {\n        sc.rawScore = -1.0;  // Hard disqualification — truncated OCR artifact\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n    ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n    : null;\n  const baseHeading = bestStructural ?? undefined;\n\n  // When the best structural heading has a continuation on the next line introduced by a\n  // punctuation token (/, &, +, :, or parenthesis), prefer the longer 2-line join as the\n  // complete heading. E.g. \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" + \"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\".\n  // Guard: the remainder after the prefix must start with a continuation character to avoid\n  // merging two separate consecutive recipe titles (FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS stays separate\n  // from FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS because \"FINNISH\" does not start with a continuation token).\n  const firstStructuralHeading = baseHeading && (\n    rawScored.find((c) => {\n      if (!isStructuralHeading(c)) return false;\n      const hLower = baseHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n      const cLower = c.text.toLowerCase();\n      return cLower.startsWith(hLower + \" \") && /^[/&+:(]/.test(cLower.slice(hLower.length + 1));\n    }) ?? baseHeading\n  );\n\n  // Pass 2: apply bonuses\n  const scored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; score: number; rawScore: number; baseScore: number; thresholdScore: number }> = rawScored.map((rs) => {\n    // Position factor: multiplicative tiebreaker — amplifies existing signal, doesn't replace it\n    const relativePosition = rs.position / lines.length;\n    const positionFactor = relativePosition < 0.5\n      ? 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - relativePosition * 2)\n      : 1.0;\n\n    // ALL_CAPS bonus: recipe books use ALL_CAPS for titles and section headings\n    const allCapsBonus = isAllCaps(rs.text) && rs.text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4\n      ? 0.08\n      : 0;\n\n    // Structural heading bonus: best ALL_CAPS heading (or its continuation join) is almost always the recipe title\n    const structuralBonus = firstStructuralHeading && rs.text === firstStructuralHeading.text ? 0.10 : 0;\n\n    // thresholdScore excludes structural bonus so the bonus doesn't inflate the threshold\n    // and prevent equally-valid structural headings from passing on multi-recipe pages.\n    const thresholdScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus;\n    // baseScore excludes position factor — used for diagnostics and ranking\n    const baseScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n    const score = rs.rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n    return { text: rs.text, position: rs.position, origin: rs.origin, score, rawScore: rs.rawScore, baseScore, thresholdScore };\n  });\n\n  if (scored.length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  // Use thresholdScore (excludes structural bonus) so the structural bonus doesn't inflate\n  // the threshold and block equally-valid headings on multi-recipe pages.\n  const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n  const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n\n  // Filter candidates above threshold\n  let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n\n  // Remove word-boundary prefixes of firstStructuralHeading when the heading itself survived\n  // the threshold. Cases:\n  //   ARAYES case:  firstStructuralHeading = \"ARAYES SHRAK\" (2-word join qualifies; \"ARAYES\"\n  //     alone = 1 word, so it never qualified). Filter removes \"ARAYES\" so dedup keeps the join.\n  //   SAFFRON case: baseHeading was the partial line; continuation logic above upgraded\n  //     firstStructuralHeading to the full join. Filter removes the partial so dedup keeps join.\n  // Safety: only fires when the complete heading itself is in selected (passed the threshold).\n  if (firstStructuralHeading && selected.some((s) => s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text)) {\n    const fshLower = firstStructuralHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n      if (s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text) return true;\n      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n      // Remove s if it is a space-delimited prefix of the structural heading\n      return !fshLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \");\n    });\n  }\n\n  // Protect continuation joins: when a multi-line join (2-line or 3-line) survived the threshold\n  // and its second part starts with a continuation character, remove the single-line prefix/suffix\n  // so the dedup \"shorter wins\" rule doesn't destroy the complete join.\n  // Note: the pre-merge step above already handles the common Baked Eggs case (&/continuation\n  // on next line) by turning it into a single candidate — this block covers the rarer case where\n  // a continuation-character join was generated as a 2-line/3-line candidate and the prefix\n  // single also survived threshold independently (e.g. from a different code path or OCR layout).\n  // Safety: only fires for joins whose continuation starts with /&+:( — digit continuations\n  // like \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki\" are NOT protected, so dedup correctly keeps the shorter form.\n  const survivingJoins = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n  if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n      if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n      // Remove PREFIX singles whose continuation join also survived\n      const isPrefixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n        if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n        const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n      });\n      if (isPrefixOfJoin) return false;\n      // Remove SUFFIX singles (e.g. \"& Coriander\") whose parent join also survived\n      const isSuffixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n        if (!jLower.endsWith(\" \" + sLower)) return false;\n        // Only remove if the suffix starts with a continuation character\n        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(sLower);\n      });\n      if (isSuffixOfJoin) return false;\n      return true;\n    });\n  }\n\n  // Deduplicate: if one title is a substring of another, keep the shorter (more focused) one.\n  // DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC — it has been incorrectly \"improved\" by the title-loop 5 times.\n  // The tests require shorter wins: \"Pierogi Ruskie\" over \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\".\n  // The pre-filter above handles the conflicting case (structural heading prefix removal) so that\n  // the incomplete prefix line is never present here when the complete join is in selected.\n  selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n    const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n    return !selected.some(\n      (b) =>\n        b !== a &&\n        aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) &&\n        b.text.length < a.text.length\n    );\n  });\n\n  // First-line mixed-case title protection:\n  // When a mixed-case title at position 0 has a reasonable score and the only ALL_CAPS\n  // candidate is at position ≤ 2 (i.e. within the first two non-empty document lines,\n  // allowing for one blank line between title and subtitle), treat the ALL_CAPS line as a\n  // subtitle/transliteration and prefer the first-line title. This handles bilingual cookbooks\n  // where the primary-language title precedes an ALL_CAPS romanization.\n  // Placement: runs AFTER dedup (so both candidates were already compared for substring overlap)\n  // but BEFORE the multi-title guard (so the guard never sees the removed subtitle as a\n  // candidate that could collapse the selection to the wrong winner).\n  // Safety: allCapsCandidates.length === 1 ensures the guard never fires on genuine multi-recipe\n  // pages (which have ≥ 2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n  if (selected.length >= 1) {\n    const pos0 = selected.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n    const allCapsCandidates = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    if (\n      pos0 &&\n      allCapsCandidates.length === 1 &&\n      allCapsCandidates[0].position <= 2 &&\n      pos0.score >= threshold\n    ) {\n      selected = selected.filter((s) => s !== allCapsCandidates[0]);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Multi-title guard: only join multiple candidates with \"+\" when there is\n  // structural evidence of a multi-recipe page (≥2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n  // A single ALL_CAPS title among mixed-case survivors is a single-recipe page —\n  // collapse to the highest-scoring candidate.\n  // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → mixed-case multi-title page → keep all.\n  if (selected.length > 1) {\n    const allCapsSelected = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n      // Check whether non-first ALL_CAPS headings are section headers within one recipe\n      // (followed immediately by ingredient-like content) rather than separate recipe titles.\n      // A multi-recipe page has body text between titles; a single-recipe page has\n      // ingredient lines immediately after each section heading.\n      const sortedCaps = [...allCapsSelected].sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n      const isSubHeader = sortedCaps.slice(1).every((cap) => {\n        const nextLines = lines.slice(cap.position + 1, cap.position + 3);\n        return nextLines.some(\n          (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n        );\n      });\n      if (isSubHeader) {\n        selected = [sortedCaps[0]];\n      } else {\n        selected = allCapsSelected;\n      }\n    } else if (allCapsSelected.length === 1) {\n      selected = [selected.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))];\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Cap at 3, sort by document position\n  selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n  selected = selected.slice(0, 3);\n\n  if (selected.length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  return selected.map((s) => s.text).join(\" + \");\n}\n\n/**\n * Extract potential recipe title from OCR text (sync heuristic fallback)\n */\nexport function extractTitle(text: string): string | undefined {\n  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\").map((line) => line.trim());\n\n  for (const line of lines) {\n    if (line.length === 0) continue;\n    if (line.length < 3 || line.length > 50) continue;\n    if (looksLikeIngredient(line)) continue;\n    if (isAllCaps(line)) continue;\n    if (startsWithNumber(line)) continue;\n    return line;\n  }\n\n  return undefined;\n}\n","numLines":542,"startLine":1,"totalLines":542}}}
